Build a CLI-based code analysis tool designed to run from the root directory of any project.

Core Requirements
1. Project Initialization
Create a /code-analysis directory in the target project
If it already exists:
Load prior state
Resume from last completed step

2. Directory Structure
/code-analysis/
manifest.json
/index/
/analyzer/
/aggregate/
/refactor/
/logs/

3. File Discovery
Recursively scan the project
EXCLUDE:
node_modules
.git
dist, build, out
coverage
any files > 500KB (log and skip)
Store all discovered files in manifest.json

Phase 1: Indexing
Batching Rules
Group files into batches based on SIZE IN BYTES
Max batch size: 50,000–60,000 bytes
Files exceeding this limit:
Process individually
Store batch definitions in manifest
Execution

For each batch:
Skip if already completed
Call LM Studio model: qwen/qwen3.5-9b
Use sequential execution (no parallelism initially)

Prompt:
You are a codebase indexing agent.
Your job is to analyze the provided files and produce a structured summary.

DO NOT suggest improvements. ONLY describe what exists.

For each file:
Identify responsibilities
List UI patterns (buttons, modals, forms, tables)
Identify key functions and purposes
Extract dependencies
Identify repeated logic patterns
Note inconsistencies

Output MUST match this JSON schema exactly:
{
  "module": "user-profile/page.tsx",
  "responsibilities": ["renders profile UI", "handles avatar upload"],
  "ui_patterns": ["modal", "form", "button.primary"],
  "data_flow": ["fetchUser()", "updateUser()"],
  "dependencies": ["api/user.ts", "components/Button.tsx"],
  "duplicated_logic_candidates": [
    {
      "description": "form validation logic",
      "similar_to": ["settings/page.tsx"]
    }
  ],
  "inconsistencies": [
    {
      "type": "UI",
      "issue": "Uses custom button instead of shared Button component"
    }
  ]
}

Output Handling:
Validate JSON before saving
Save per batch:
/code-analysis/index/batch-XXX.json

Update manifest with:
batch status
timestamp
success/failure
Retry failed batches up to 2 times

Phase 2: Analysis
Input:
Load indexed batch outputs
Combine into GROUPS (not all at once)
Each group ≤ ~80KB

Model:
qwen/qwen3.5-9b (default)
Optional upgrade to gemma-4-e4b

Prompt:
You are a codebase consistency analyzer.

Your job:
Identify duplicated logic
Identify inconsistent UI patterns
Identify inconsistent architecture
Group similar implementations

Output:
duplication_clusters
ui_inconsistencies
architecture_inconsistencies
candidate_shared_components
candidate_utility_functions
Output

/code-analysis/analyzer/group-XXX.json

Phase 3: Aggregation
Input: 
All analyzer outputs (chunk if needed)

Model: 
Claude Sonnet 4.6 (via Claude Code)

Prompt:
Your job:
Define STANDARD patterns for:
UI components (buttons, forms, modals)
Data fetching
State management
Routing
Error handling
File structure
Define a TARGET ARCHITECTURE:
Shared components
Utility modules
Folder organization
For each inconsistency:
Decide the correct approach
Explain why
Output a “Codebase Standards Document” and “Refactor Strategy”
This should be opinionated, consistent, and optimized for maintainability.

Output:
/code-analysis/aggregate/standards.md
/code-analysis/aggregate/refactor-strategy.md

Phase 4: Refactor Planning
Batching
Group modules by:
feature
directory
dependency cluster

Model:
qwen/qwen3.5-9b

Prompt:
You are a refactor planning agent.
You will receive:
A standards document
A small subset of modules
Your job:
Identify all deviations from standards
Generate a step-by-step modification plan
For each change:
File
Exact code change
Before/after pattern
Dependencies impacted
Tests to validate
Constraints:
Changes must be atomic and reversible
Do not exceed the provided module scope

Output:
/code-analysis/refactor/plan-XXX.md

CLI Interface:
The tool must support:
--phase=index
--phase=analyze
--phase=aggregate
--phase=refactor

Optional:
--resume
--max-batch-size
--model-override

Reliability Requirements
All phases must be resumable
All outputs must be persisted immediately
Each batch must be idempotent
Failures must not corrupt state
Logging
Log all activity to:
/code-analysis/logs/run.log

Include:
batch start/end
errors
retries
model used
Design Constraints
Minimize context size per AI call
Prefer more batches over oversized batches
Maintain deterministic outputs
No parallel execution in initial version




